{"title_page": "Grigor Cilka", "text_new": "{{Infobox person  \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Grigor Cilka\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Grigor Cilka with wife Katerina Stefanova-Cilka and their baby.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Grigor Cilka with wife [[Katerina Cilka]] and daughter Eleni\n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = 1875 \n| birth_place      = [[Vithkuq]], [[Ottoman Empire]] (present-day [[Albania]])\n| death_date       = 1919\n| death_place      = [[Bulgaria]] \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = reverend, missionary, teacher\n| language         = \n| nationality      = \n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       =\n| period           = \n| genre            = \n| subject          = \n| movement         = [[Albanian National Awakening]]\n| notableworks     = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| website          = \n| portaldisp       = \n}}\n'''Grigor Cilka''' (1875-1919) was an [[Albanians|Albanian]] Protestant reverend and missionary.<ref name=\"Walton192\"/><ref name=\"Clayer618\"/> In the height of the [[Albanian National Awakening]] he became a teacher at the first Albanian school for girls in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]].<ref name=\"Myzyri132\"/><ref name=\"Skendi136156\"/>\n\n==Life==\nGrigor Cilka was born in 1875 in [[Vithkuq]]. The family later moved to [[Bitola|Monastir]].<ref name=\"Myzyri132\"/> He was educated at missionary schools in Monastir, and later [[Samokov]].<ref name=\"Walton192\"/> Cilka was a convert from [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christianity]] to [[Protestant Christianity]].<ref name=\"Clayer315618\">{{cite book|last=Clayer|first=Nathalie|title=Aux origines du nationalisme albanais: La naissance d\u2019une nation majoritairement musulmane en Europe [The origins of Albanian nationalism: The birth of a predominantly Muslim nation in Europe]|year=2007|location=Paris|publisher=Karthala|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xISnDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Aux+origines+du+nationalisme+albanais:+la+naissance+d%27une+nation+majoritairement+musulmane+en+Europe&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT_9TT9fLoAhXCzDgGHUQrCAkQ6AEIJzAA#v=snippet&q=Cilka&f=false|isbn=9782845868168|pages=315, 618.|ref=harv}}</ref> He went to [[New York City]], [[United States]] to finish his education at the [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]].<ref name=\"Walton192\"/> During his stay in the US, Cilka in 1899 married [[Katerina Cilka]], a Bulgarian nurse and Protestant from [[Bansko]].<ref name=\"Walton192\"/><ref name=\"Thanailaki81\"/> In the summer following their marriage, they returned, settled in Kor\u00e7\u00eb and dedicated their efforts toward missionary work, teaching and humanitarian activities in surrounding villages.<ref name=\"Walton192\"/><ref name=\"Thanailaki81\"/><ref name=\"Daniel134\">{{harvnb|Daniel|1970|p=134.}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherman25\">{{harvnb|Sherman|1980|p=25.}}</ref> Cilka founded a Protestant parish in Kor\u00e7\u00eb.<ref name=\"Sherman27\">{{harvnb|Sherman|1980|p=27.}}</ref> After studying [[theology]], Cilka became a member of Kor\u00e7\u00eb-based organisations that sought the creation of an Albanian state independent of the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=\"Ermenji237\"/><ref name=\"Daniel142\">{{harvnb|Daniel|1970|p=142.}}</ref> In the late nineteenth century debate over choosing an Albanian alphabet, Cilka was a supporter of the [[Albanian alphabet#National awakening 19th-century endeavours|Frash\u00ebri alphabet]].<ref name=\"Clayer618\">{{harvnb|Clayer|2007|p=618.}}</ref> Together with his wife Katerina, Cilka served as teacher at the first Albanian school for girls in Kor\u00e7\u00eb.<ref name=\"Myzyri132\"/><ref name=\"Skendi136156\">{{harvnb|Skendi|1967|pp=136, 156.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1901, Katerina, pregnant for 6 months, embarked on a regional tour with, and at the invitation of her friend American Protestant missionary Ellen Maria Stone.<ref name=\"Walton192\"/><ref name=\"Thanailaki81\"/> Both were kidnapped by [[Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization]] (IMRO) members who ransomed them for money<ref name=\"Walton192\">{{cite book|last=Walton|first=Andrea|title=Women and Philanthropy in Education|year=|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253111319|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=5hBbtn2KhjwC&pg=PA182&dq=Gregory+Tsilka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZhOH0w_joAhWQA3IKHQs1AokQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=Gregory%20Tsilka&f=false|pages=192|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Thanailaki81\">{{cite book|last=Thanailaki|first=Polly|title=Gender Inequalities in Rural European Communities During 19th and Early 20th Century: A Historical Perspective|year=2018|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319752358|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WpxPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA81&dq=Grigor+Tsilka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEi__IvvjoAhWGzTgGHU-7BBMQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=Grigor%20Tsilka&f=false|pages=81|ref=harv}}</ref> in what become known internationally as the [[Miss Stone Affair]]. Ottoman authorities suspected Protestants of involvement and for a short time, Cilka was arrested on orders by the [[W\u0101li#Ottoman Empire term|vali]] (governor) of [[Salonika]] on unfounded charges of being complicit in the kidnapping.<ref name=\"Perry104\">{{cite book|last=Perry|first=Duncan M.|title=The Politics of Terror: The Macedonian Liberation Movements, 1893-1903|year=1988|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822308133|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=OTxtAAAAMAAJ&q=Grigor+Tsilka&dq=Grigor+Tsilka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEi__IvvjoAhWGzTgGHU-7BBMQ6AEISjAE|pages=104|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Daniel135\">{{cite book|last=Daniel|first=Robert L.|title=American philanthropy in the Near East, 1820-1960|year=1970|publisher=Ohio University Press|isbn=9780821400630|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=hXxtAAAAMAAJ&q=Gregory+Tsilka&dq=Gregory+Tsilka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZhOH0w_joAhWQA3IKHQs1AokQ6AEIbjAJ|pages=135|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherman89\">{{harvnb|Sherman|1980|p=[https://books.google.com.au/books?id=9pdpAAAAMAAJ&dq=Katerina+Grigor+Tsilka+Eleni&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Grigor+Tsilka 89].}}</ref> The Cilkas returned to Kor\u00e7\u00eb and authorities from the Ottoman state continued to suspect the couple of involvement in the event.<ref name=\"Sherman98\"/> The couple had a daughter named Eleni.<ref name=\"Sherman98\"/> During the IMRO [[Ilinden Uprising]] against the Ottoman Empire (1903), to prevent additional persecution by the Ottomans, the [[Austro-Hungarian]] consul assisted the couple to temporarily flee the region.<ref name=\"Sherman98\">{{cite book|last=Sherman|first=Laura Beth|title=Fires on the Mountain: The Macedonian Revolutionary Movement and the Kidnapping of Ellen Stone|year=1980|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780914710554|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=9pdpAAAAMAAJ&dq=Katerina+Grigor+Tsilka+Eleni&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Kortcha|pages=98|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn 1908, Cilka was a delegate to the [[Congress of Manastir]], an [[academic conference]] with the goal of standardizing the [[Albanian alphabet]]. He was active in contemporary public discussions over culture and education in Ottoman territories with Albanian populations, and supported in various newspapers the usage of [[Latin script]] to write Albanian.<ref name=\"Ermenji237\"/> To boost education and intellectual thought among Albanian people, Cilka promoted various literary works known around the world.<ref name=\"Myzyri132\">{{cite book|last=Myzyri|first=Hysni|title=Pandeli J. Evangjeli, 1859 - 1949: atdhetar dhe burr\u00eb shteti i shquar|year=2004|publisher=Albpaper|isbn=9994360175|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=lXktAQAAIAAJ&dq=Malli+i+M%C3%ABm%C3%ABdheut&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Grigor+Cilka|pages=132|ref=harv}}</ref> Cilka served as director of the girls' school, later he was imprisoned by Ottoman authorities and the educational institution closed shortly thereafter in February 1904.<ref name=\"Skendi137\">{{harvnb|Skendi|1967|p=137.}}</ref> In 1906, an Albanian guerilla band assassinated Greek bishop [[Photios of Korytsa|Photios]] and Ottoman authorities unable to arrest the perpetrators, had Cilka and other Kor\u00e7\u00eb Albanian notables involved in the national movement imprisoned, but released soon after.<ref name=\"Skendi210\">{{harvnb|Skendi|1967|p=210.}}</ref> Cilka in 1906 was involved in the establishment of groups geared toward nationalist aims.<ref name=\"Skendi156\">{{cite book|last=Skendi|first=Stavro|title=The Albanian National Awakening|year=1967|location=Princeton|publisher=Princeton University Press|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?hl=en&lr=&id=8QPWCgAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PR15&dq=The+Albanian+National+Awakening&ots=zGjQbVyql8&sig=xsmbL-yAAtc-ny3v0E4vN87JOBY&redir_esc=y#v=snippet&q=Cilka&f=false|isbn=9781400847761|pages=156.|ref=harv}}</ref> After [[Albanian Declaration of Independence|the declaration of independence]], Cilka moved to [[Bulgaria]] where he died in 1919 from the [[Spanish flu]].<ref name=\"Ermenji237\">{{cite book|last=Ermenji|first=Abas|title=Vendi q\u00eb z\u00eb Sk\u00ebnderbeu n\u00eb historin\u00eb e Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb|year=1996|publisher=\u00c7abej|isbn=|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=r4e4AAAAIAAJ&dq=Vendi+q%C3%AB+z%C3%AB+Sk%C3%ABnderbeu+n%C3%AB+historin%C3%AB+e+Shqip%C3%ABris%C3%AB&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Grigor+Cilka|pages=237|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[M\u00ebsonj\u00ebtorja]]\n*[[Albanian Alphabet]]\n*[[Education in Albania]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Carpenter|first=Teresa|title=The Miss Stone Affair: America's First Modern Hostage Crisis|year=2004|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9780743258050|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=az0Skf467RwC&dq=Katerina+Tsilka+Gregory&q=Grigory#v=snippet&q=Grigor&f=false|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cochran|first=Richard M.|title=Katerina Stephanova Tsilka|year=2014|publisher=Institute for Albanian & Protestant Studies|isbn=|url=http://www.instituti.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/COCHRAN-Katerina-Tsilka-Biography1.pdf}}\n\n\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:Albanian educators]]\n[[Category:Albanian Protestants]]\n[[Category:Albanian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:People from Bitola]]\n[[Category:Activists of the Albanian National Awakening]]\n[[Category:People from Manastir Vilayet]]\n[[Category:19th-century Albanian people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Albanian people]]\n[[Category:Converts to Protestantism from Eastern Orthodoxy]]\n[[Category:Union Theological Seminary (New York City) alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person  \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Grigor Cilka\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Grigor Cilka with wife Katerina Stefanova-Cilka and their baby.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Grigor Cilka with wife Katerina Stefanova-Cilka and daughter Eleni\n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = 1875 \n| birth_place      = [[Vithkuq]], [[Ottoman Empire]] (present-day [[Albania]])\n| death_date       = 1919\n| death_place      = [[Bulgaria]] \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = reverend, missionary, teacher\n| language         = \n| nationality      = \n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       =\n| period           = \n| genre            = \n| subject          = \n| movement         = [[Albanian National Awakening]]\n| notableworks     = \n| spouse           = \n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| website          = \n| portaldisp       = \n}}\n'''Grigor Cilka''' (1875-1919) was an [[Albanians|Albanian]] Protestant reverend and missionary.<ref name=\"Walton192\"/><ref name=\"Clayer618\"/> In the height of the [[Albanian National Awakening]] he became a teacher at the first Albanian school for girls in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]].<ref name=\"Myzyri132\"/><ref name=\"Skendi136156\"/>\n\n==Life==\nGrigor Cilka was born in 1875 in [[Vithkuq]]. The family later moved to [[Bitola|Monastir]].<ref name=\"Myzyri132\"/> He was educated at missionary schools in Monastir, and later [[Samokov]].<ref name=\"Walton192\"/> Cilka was a convert from [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christianity]] to [[Protestant Christianity]].<ref name=\"Clayer315618\">{{cite book|last=Clayer|first=Nathalie|title=Aux origines du nationalisme albanais: La naissance d\u2019une nation majoritairement musulmane en Europe [The origins of Albanian nationalism: The birth of a predominantly Muslim nation in Europe]|year=2007|location=Paris|publisher=Karthala|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=xISnDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=Aux+origines+du+nationalisme+albanais:+la+naissance+d%27une+nation+majoritairement+musulmane+en+Europe&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiT_9TT9fLoAhXCzDgGHUQrCAkQ6AEIJzAA#v=snippet&q=Cilka&f=false|isbn=9782845868168|pages=315, 618.|ref=harv}}</ref> He went to [[New York City]], [[United States]] to finish his education at the [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]].<ref name=\"Walton192\"/> During his stay in the US, Cilka in 1899 married [[Katerina Cilka]], a Bulgarian nurse and Protestant from [[Bansko]].<ref name=\"Walton192\"/><ref name=\"Thanailaki81\"/> In the summer following their marriage, they returned, settled in Kor\u00e7\u00eb and dedicated their efforts toward missionary work, teaching and humanitarian activities in surrounding villages.<ref name=\"Walton192\"/><ref name=\"Thanailaki81\"/><ref name=\"Daniel134\">{{harvnb|Daniel|1970|p=134.}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherman25\">{{harvnb|Sherman|1980|p=25.}}</ref> Cilka founded a Protestant parish in Kor\u00e7\u00eb.<ref name=\"Sherman27\">{{harvnb|Sherman|1980|p=27.}}</ref> After studying [[theology]], Cilka became a member of Kor\u00e7\u00eb-based organisations that sought the creation of an Albanian state independent of the [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=\"Ermenji237\"/><ref name=\"Daniel142\">{{harvnb|Daniel|1970|p=142.}}</ref> In the late nineteenth century debate over choosing an Albanian alphabet, Cilka was a supporter of the [[Albanian alphabet#National awakening 19th-century endeavours|Frash\u00ebri alphabet]].<ref name=\"Clayer618\">{{harvnb|Clayer|2007|p=618.}}</ref> Together with his wife Katerina, Cilka served as teacher at the first Albanian school for girls in Kor\u00e7\u00eb.<ref name=\"Myzyri132\"/><ref name=\"Skendi136156\">{{harvnb|Skendi|1967|pp=136, 156.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1901, Katerina, pregnant for 6 months, embarked on a regional tour with, and at the invitation of her friend American Protestant missionary Ellen Maria Stone.<ref name=\"Walton192\"/><ref name=\"Thanailaki81\"/> Both were kidnapped by [[Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization]] (IMRO) members who ransomed them for money<ref name=\"Walton192\">{{cite book|last=Walton|first=Andrea|title=Women and Philanthropy in Education|year=|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253111319|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=5hBbtn2KhjwC&pg=PA182&dq=Gregory+Tsilka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZhOH0w_joAhWQA3IKHQs1AokQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=Gregory%20Tsilka&f=false|pages=192|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Thanailaki81\">{{cite book|last=Thanailaki|first=Polly|title=Gender Inequalities in Rural European Communities During 19th and Early 20th Century: A Historical Perspective|year=2018|publisher=Springer|isbn=9783319752358|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WpxPDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA81&dq=Grigor+Tsilka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEi__IvvjoAhWGzTgGHU-7BBMQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=Grigor%20Tsilka&f=false|pages=81|ref=harv}}</ref> in what become known internationally as the [[Miss Stone Affair]]. Ottoman authorities suspected Protestants of involvement and for a short time, Cilka was arrested on orders by the [[W\u0101li#Ottoman Empire term|vali]] (governor) of [[Salonika]] on unfounded charges of being complicit in the kidnapping.<ref name=\"Perry104\">{{cite book|last=Perry|first=Duncan M.|title=The Politics of Terror: The Macedonian Liberation Movements, 1893-1903|year=1988|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=9780822308133|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=OTxtAAAAMAAJ&q=Grigor+Tsilka&dq=Grigor+Tsilka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEi__IvvjoAhWGzTgGHU-7BBMQ6AEISjAE|pages=104|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Daniel135\">{{cite book|last=Daniel|first=Robert L.|title=American philanthropy in the Near East, 1820-1960|year=1970|publisher=Ohio University Press|isbn=9780821400630|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=hXxtAAAAMAAJ&q=Gregory+Tsilka&dq=Gregory+Tsilka&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZhOH0w_joAhWQA3IKHQs1AokQ6AEIbjAJ|pages=135|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=\"Sherman89\">{{harvnb|Sherman|1980|p=[https://books.google.com.au/books?id=9pdpAAAAMAAJ&dq=Katerina+Grigor+Tsilka+Eleni&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Grigor+Tsilka 89].}}</ref> The Cilkas returned to Kor\u00e7\u00eb and authorities from the Ottoman state continued to suspect the couple of involvement in the event.<ref name=\"Sherman98\"/> The couple had a daughter named Eleni.<ref name=\"Sherman98\"/> During the IMRO [[Ilinden Uprising]] against the Ottoman Empire (1903), to prevent additional persecution by the Ottomans, the [[Austro-Hungarian]] consul assisted the couple to temporarily flee the region.<ref name=\"Sherman98\">{{cite book|last=Sherman|first=Laura Beth|title=Fires on the Mountain: The Macedonian Revolutionary Movement and the Kidnapping of Ellen Stone|year=1980|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=9780914710554|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=9pdpAAAAMAAJ&dq=Katerina+Grigor+Tsilka+Eleni&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Kortcha|pages=98|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nIn 1908, Cilka was a delegate to the [[Congress of Manastir]], an [[academic conference]] with the goal of standardizing the [[Albanian alphabet]]. He was active in contemporary public discussions over culture and education in Ottoman territories with Albanian populations, and supported in various newspapers the usage of [[Latin script]] to write Albanian.<ref name=\"Ermenji237\"/> To boost education and intellectual thought among Albanian people, Cilka promoted various literary works known around the world.<ref name=\"Myzyri132\">{{cite book|last=Myzyri|first=Hysni|title=Pandeli J. Evangjeli, 1859 - 1949: atdhetar dhe burr\u00eb shteti i shquar|year=2004|publisher=Albpaper|isbn=9994360175|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=lXktAQAAIAAJ&dq=Malli+i+M%C3%ABm%C3%ABdheut&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Grigor+Cilka|pages=132|ref=harv}}</ref> Cilka served as director of the girls' school, later he was imprisoned by Ottoman authorities and the educational institution closed shortly thereafter in February 1904.<ref name=\"Skendi137\">{{harvnb|Skendi|1967|p=137.}}</ref> In 1906, an Albanian guerilla band assassinated Greek bishop [[Photios of Korytsa|Photios]] and Ottoman authorities unable to arrest the perpetrators, had Cilka and other Kor\u00e7\u00eb Albanian notables involved in the national movement imprisoned, but released soon after.<ref name=\"Skendi210\">{{harvnb|Skendi|1967|p=210.}}</ref> Cilka in 1906 was involved in the establishment of groups geared toward nationalist aims.<ref name=\"Skendi156\">{{cite book|last=Skendi|first=Stavro|title=The Albanian National Awakening|year=1967|location=Princeton|publisher=Princeton University Press|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?hl=en&lr=&id=8QPWCgAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PR15&dq=The+Albanian+National+Awakening&ots=zGjQbVyql8&sig=xsmbL-yAAtc-ny3v0E4vN87JOBY&redir_esc=y#v=snippet&q=Cilka&f=false|isbn=9781400847761|pages=156.|ref=harv}}</ref> After [[Albanian Declaration of Independence|the declaration of independence]], Cilka moved to [[Bulgaria]] where he died in 1919 from the [[Spanish flu]].<ref name=\"Ermenji237\">{{cite book|last=Ermenji|first=Abas|title=Vendi q\u00eb z\u00eb Sk\u00ebnderbeu n\u00eb historin\u00eb e Shqip\u00ebris\u00eb|year=1996|publisher=\u00c7abej|isbn=|url=https://b