{"title_page": "List of Indian Christians", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}This article '''lists notable [[Indian people|Indian]] [[Christians]]'''. The list includes both Indians who lived within India and its predecessor states, and those of Indian ancestry who reided other countries.\n\n== Freedom fighters ==\n* [[Kali Charan Banerjee]] (1847\u20131902)<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.theway.org.uk/Back/s104Gispert-Sauch.pdf |title=Two-Eyed Dialogue: Reflections after Fifty Years |first=George |last=Gispert-Suach |quote=the Rev. Kali Charan Banerjee, himself a convert to the Anglican Church. |journal=The Way |year=2002 |volume=104 (Suppement) |pages=31\u201341 |accessdate=2014-06-10}}</ref>\n*[[Krishna Mohan Banerjee]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Murshid |first=Ghulam |year=2012 |chapter=Banerji, Rev. Krishna Mohan |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Banerji,_Rev._Krishna_Mohan |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>\n*[[Amrit Kaur]]<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Who is an Indian? |first=Judith M. |last=Brown |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NCvZWNkQxkC&pg=PA130 |page=130 |title=Missions, Nationalism and the End of Empire |editor1-first=Stanley |editor1-last=Brian |editor2-first=Alaine M. |editor2-last=Low |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |year=2003 |isbn=978-0-80282-116-4}}</ref>\n*[[Harendra Coomar Mookerjee]]<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Who is an Indian? |first=Judith M. |last=Brown |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NCvZWNkQxkC&pg=PA129 |page=129 |title=Missions, Nationalism and the End of Empire |editor1-first=Stanley |editor1-last=Brian |editor2-first=Alaine M. |editor2-last=Low |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |year=2003 |isbn=978-0-80282-116-4}}</ref>\n*[[Pandita Ramabai]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Jayawardena |first=Kumari |title=The White Woman's Other Burden : Western Women and South Asia During British Colonial Rule |year=1995 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-13665-707-8 |page=55 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vjdpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA55}}</ref>\n*[[S. K. Rudra]]<ref>{{cite book |last=O'Connor |first=Daniel |title=A Clear Star: C. F. Andrews and India 1904 -1914 |year=2005 |publisher=Chronicle Books |page=37|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m1wJ3zXnSr0C&pg=PA37 |isbn=978-8-18028-023-8}}</ref>\n*[[J.C. Kumarappa]]\n*[[Joseph Baptista]]\n*[[Joachim Alva]]\n\n== Business ==\n\n*[[M. G. George Muthoot]], Chairman of [[Muthoot]] Group<ref>{{cite news |work=Muthoot News |title=The leader, the higher order was looking for |url=http://www.stmarysorthodoxchurchfaridabad.org/images/LayTrustree_MGeorgeMuthoot.pdf |accessdate=2017-02-08 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728061810/http://www.stmarysorthodoxchurchfaridabad.org/images/LayTrustree_MGeorgeMuthoot.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-28}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\n*[[Ajit Jogi]] 1st [[Chief Minister of Chattisgarh]] \n*[[Y. S. Jaganmohan Reddy]] current [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]]\n*[[George Fernandes]] was an Indian trade unionist, statesman, journalist, freethinker \n*[[S C Jamir]] Former Chief Minister of Nagaland, and former Governor of Maharashtra and Odisha. \n*[[Madhusudan Das]]\n*[[A. J. John]], founder leader of Travancore State Congress<ref name=\"auto\">Fr. George Thalian: {{cite web|url=http://geocities.ws/kandathil/kandathil/kandathil.html |title=' ''The Great Archbishop Mar Augustine Kandathil, D. D.: the Outline of a Vocation'' '}}, Mar Louis Memorial Press, 1961</ref> \n* [[Y. S. Rajasekhara Reddy]] (1949\u20132009), former [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.merinews.com/article/ysr-buried-with-full-state-honour-in-idupulapai/15783520.shtml |title=YSR buried with full state honour in Idupulapai |date=5 September 2009 |work=Merinews |first=V. Gopala Krishan |last=Murthy |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref>\n* [[Sangliana]], Police Officer of Karnataka, originally from Mizoram, who also served as a Member of the Parliament of India<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/meghalaya-bjp-puts-its-sole-christian-mp-at/275406/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126102825/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/meghalaya-bjp-puts-its-sole-christian-mp-at/275406/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 January 2013 |title=Meghalaya: BJP puts its sole Christian MP at work |work=Indian Express |date=21 February 2008 |accessdate=2012-05-29}}</ref>\n* [[Lal Thanhawla]], Chief Minister of [[Mizoram]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-04-27/guwahati/38861208_1_mnf-mizoram-congress-mizo-national-front | work=The Times Of India | title=Mizo National Front heat on Mizoram CM over 'idol worship' | access-date=27 September 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019051550/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-04-27/guwahati/38861208_1_mnf-mizoram-congress-mizo-national-front | archive-date=19 October 2013 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[A. K. Antony]] Former Kerala Chief minister and Indian defenese minister\n* [[Oommen Chandy]] Former Kerala Chief minister\n* [[Rishang Keishing]] Former Chief Minister of Manipur. \n* [[K. M. Mani]] Previous Minister of Finance and law from Kerala\n* [[Neiphiu Rio]] Chief Minister of Nagaland. \n* [[T. M. Thomas Isaac]] Minister of Finance of Kerala\n* [[P. C. Alexander]] IAS officer, Previous Governor of Tamil Nadu & Maharashtra\n* [[P. C. George]] An MLA from Poonjar, Kerala assembly\n\n== Cinema ==\n*[[Katrina Kaif]], British Indian Bollywood actress, highest paid actress in India,<ref>http://biogtown.com/actress-katrina-kaif-biography-personal-life-marriage-controversy-wiki/</ref> CEO- Kay Beauty \n*[[Samantha Akkineni]],South indian actress\n*[[Nivetha Thomas]],south indian actress\n*[[Vijay (actor)|Vijay]], Kollywood actor<ref>https://tamilglitz.in/the-23-a-tribute-to-ilayathalapathy-vijay-for-his-23-years-of-excellence/</ref>\n*[[Nivin Pauly]], Mollywood actor\n*[[Vikram (actor)]], Kollywood actor\n*[[Tovino Thomas]],Mollywood actor\n*[[Dino Morea]], Hindi cinema actor<ref>{{cite web|title = I've had long conversations with God here: Dino Morea about Mount Mary Church|url = http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-i-ve-had-long-conversations-with-god-here-dino-morea-about-mount-mary-church-1738268|accessdate=2015-10-01}}</ref>\n*[[Johny Lever]], Hindhi cinema actor\n*[[Tiger Prabhakar]], Kannada cinema actor<ref>{{cite web|title = My Dad Prabhakar Did not Die of Gangrene: Vinod Prabhakar - chitraloka.com {{!}} Kannada Movie News, Reviews {{!}} Image|url = http://www.chitraloka.com/interviews/11793-my-dad-prabhakar-did-not-die-of-gangrene-vinod-prabhakar.html|website = www.chitraloka.com|accessdate=2015-10-02|first = Super|last = User}}</ref>\n*\n\n== Sports ==\n* [[Sanju Samson]], cricketer\n* [[Varun Aaron]], cricketer\n*[[Mahesh Bhupathi]], professional tennis player also widely regarded as among the best [[doubles (tennis)|doubles]] players in the world with 11 [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] titles to his credit<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi-times/Shvetha-Mahesh-Why-knot/articleshow/20992167.cms | work=The Times Of India | first=Gauri | last=Sinh | title=Shvetha & Mahesh? Why knot! | date=2 September 2002 |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref>\n*[[Vinod Kambli]], cricketer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report_vinod-kambli-embraces-christianity_1435521 |title=Vinod Kambli embraces Christianity - Sport - DNA |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date= 9 September 2010|accessdate=2013-09-25}}</ref>\n*[[Mary Kom]], Olympic bronze medallist in [[2012 Summer Olympics]], London<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.readersdigest.co.in/mary-kom |title=Mary Kom: Full-Confidence Lady |publisher=Reader's Digest |author=Aarti Narang |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227052910/http://www.readersdigest.co.in/mary-kom |archivedate=27 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Religious leaders ==\n\n*[[Philipose Mar Chrysostom|Dr.Philipose Mar Chrysostom]] - Padma Bushan,world record holder for the longest serving bishop in the world, record holder as theme actor in the longest comprehensive biopic documentary ever made<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Blessys-biopic-on-Mar-Chrysostom-will-be-72-hours-long/articleshow/52671550.cms|title=Blessy's biopic on Mar Chrysostom will be 72 hours long - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/mohanlal-blessy-back-with-documentary-on-mar-chrysostom.html|title=Mohanlal, Blessy back again for documentary on Mar Chrysostom|website=OnManorama|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>,Metropolitan Emeritus of the [[Mar Thoma Syrian Church]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Mar Thoma|first=Alexander|title=The Syrian heritage and the Mar Thoma Church|date=2011-12-31|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.31826/9781463232931-003|work=The Harp (Volume 2)|pages=9\u201310|publisher=Gorgias Press|isbn=978-1-4632-3293-1|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n*[[Baselios Mar Thoma Paulose II]] - 8th Catholicos of the Malankara & 21st [[Malankara Metropolitan]] (2010\u2013Present).(Supreme head of the [[Malankara  Orthodox Church|Malankara Church]] aka Indian Orthodox Church)\n*[[Andrews Thazhath]] - the third and the [[Metropolitan Archbishop]] of [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Archdiocese of Thrissur]]\n*[[Jacob Thoomkuzhy]] - Catholic Arch Bishop Emeritus and the second [[Metropolitan Archbishop]] of the [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Archdiocese of Thrissur]]\n* [[Joseph Mar Thoma]] - [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]] of the [[Mar Thoma Syrian Church]].\n* [[Jolly Abraham]] - Leading [[evangelism|evangelist]] [[worship leader]] in South India. Founder of Musi-Care Cultural and Charitable Trust<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/jollee-good-show/article2030431.ece |title=Jollee good show! |work=The Hindu |date=19 May 2011 |accessdate=2016-09-15}}</ref>\n* [[Puroshottam Choudhary]] - preacher, evangelist, writer of [[Christian literature]]\n* [[Aurobindo Nath Mukherjee]] - first Indian [[Anglican Diocese of Calcutta|Bishop of Calcutta]] and [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan of India]]\n* [[Lal Behari Dey]] - Indian journalist, writer, and Christian missionary\n* [[Ravi Zacharias]] - Christian apologist, Founder and Chairman of the Board of Ravi Zacharias International Ministries.\n* [[D. G. S. Dhinakaran]] - Christian evangelist. \n*[[Paul Dhinakaran]], Indian evangelist and the Chancellor of [[Karunya university]], which he owns. \n*[[K. A. Paul]], Evangelist,Philanthropist, Politician and founder of [[Praja Shanti Party]]. \n*[[K. P. Yohannan]], founder and president of [[Gospel for Asia]], He is also the founder and Metropolitan Bishop of [[Believers Eastern Church]]. \n* [[Valerian Gracias]] - First cardinal from India.\n* [[Duraisamy Simon Lourdusamy]] - First Indian to head a [[Sacred Congregation]] of the [[Catholic Church]].\n* [[Acharya K. K. Chandy]] - President Emeritus- Fellowship of Reconciliation India; 1 of the 3 Founding Fathers - Christavashram, Kottayam; Founder Father- Gurukul Ecumenical Centre for Peace. \n* [[Varghese Payyappilly Palakkappilly]] - Founder of the Congregation of the [[Sisters of the Destitute]].\n* [[Mary Celine Payyappilly]] - [[Servant of God]], Professed Religious of the Congregation of the Mother of Carmel.\n* [[George Alencherry]] - [[Catholic Cardinal]] and the Major Archbishop of the [[Syro-Malabar Church]].\n* [[Varkey Vithayathil]] - [[Catholic Cardinal]] and former Major Archbishop of the [[Syro-Malabar Church]].\n* [[Antony Padiyara]] - [[Catholic Cardinal]] and the First Major Archbishop of the [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Church]].\n* [[Joseph Parecattil]] - First from the Syro-Malabar church to be made a [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]].\n* [[Augustine Kandathil]] - First head of the [[Syro-Malabar Church]] and first Indian to assume powers and rule as an [[archbishop]] of the [[Catholic Church]].\n* [[Kuriakose Elias Chavara]] - First Indian to be beatified [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Church]].\n* [[Saint Alphonsa]] - first Indian Catholic to be raised to sainthood [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Church]].\n* [[Mother Teresa]] of Kolkata - Founder of [[Missionaries of Charity]] and the most well-known Christian social worker of India (although Albanian and born in Skopje in Macedonia, she became an Indian).\n* [[V. C. Samuel]] - World-renowned [[Theologian]], [[Historian]], [[Ecumenical]] Leader, [[Professor]]/[[Dean (education)|Dean]] in India and abroad, [[Priest]], [[Indian Orthodox Church]].\n* [[Cyril Baselios]] - Former head of the [[Syro-Malankara Catholic Church]].\n* [[Mariam Thresia]] - [[Syro-Malabar Church]].\n* St. [[Euphrasia]] - [[Syro-Malabar Church]].\n* St. [[Joseph Vaz]] - Goan [[Oratory of Saint Philip Neri|Oratorian]] [[priest]] and missionary to [[Sri Lanka]]\n*[[Rani Maria Vattalil]] - Catholic religious and missionary social worker in the Franciscan Clarist Congregation\n* [[Nidhiry Mani Kathanar]] - Priest of the [[Syro-Malabar Church]] who led a relentless campaign for indigenous bishops. Founder of Nazrani Deepika Malayalam newspaper.\n* [[Neiliezh\u00fc \u00dcsou]] (1941\u20132009), an influential Baptist preacher, theologian, Church musician, music teacher and composer from the [[North-East India|North-Eastern state of India]], [[Nagaland]].\n* [[Baselios Yeldo]] - was the Maphrian of the East of the Syriac Orthodox Church. He was the Catholicos of Jerusalem and Mosul. He is the Saint of Malankara Orthodox, Syriac Orthodox and Jacobite Orthodox Churches.\n* [[Baselios Mar Thoma Mathews I]] - First Catholicos who used Mar Thoma in his title. He was awarded The Order of St. Valdimer by the Patriarch of Russia.\n* [[Antonio Francisco Xavier Alvares]] - First Head of Goan Orthodox who was a Catholic Priest who joined Malankara Orthodox Syrian Church in search for real believes and worship.\n* [[J. W. Gladstone]] - Moderator of the [[Church of South India]].\n* [[K. C. John]] - [[India Pentecostal Church of God]] General President.\n* [[Telesphore Toppo]] - First Indian Cardinal from the Scheduled Tribal communities.\n* [[Devasahayam Pillai]] (1712\u20131752), beatified convert, layman and martyr of the Latin rite of the Roman Catholic Church.\n* [[Geevarghese Mar Gregorios|Geevarghese Gregorios]] - (1848-1902)  First Indian to be raised to sainthood. First Saint of Malankara Church and the youngest one in Malankara to become a Bishop.\n* [[Geevarghese Mar Dionysius of Vattasseril (Dionysius VI)|Geevarghese Dionysius of Vattasseril (Dionysius VI)]] (1858-1934) Malankara Metropolitan and Saint of Malankara Orthodox Church.\n* [[Thomas Fernando]], former Catholic bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tuticorin]]\n* [[Francis Tiburtius Roche]], former Catholic bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tuticorin]]\n* [[Peter Fernando]], former Catholic bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tuticorin]]\n\n=== Others in religious life ===\n*[[Siluvai Ignaci]] - Catholic Priest and Educator from [[Kuthenkuly]]\n* [[Maria Theresa Chiramel]] - Catholic nun.\n* [[Ken Gnanakan]] - Evangelist, singer, environmentalist and Founder Director of Acts Ministries.\n* [[P. C. John]] - [[Kerala Brethren]] person.\n* [[Nirmala Joshi]] - Former Superior General of the [[Missionaries of Charity]].\n* [[Bakht Singh]] - Evangelist, Apostle and Pioneer in local Church planting Ministries in India.\n* [[Sadhu Sundar Singh]] - Missionary, [[Universal Reconciliation|Christian universalist]].\n* [[Sadhu Kochoonju Upadesi]] - Malayali preacher and poet / composer.\n\n== Cultural leaders ==\n*[[Michael Madhusudan Dutt]] - famous Bengali poet and dramatist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boloji.com/index.cfm?md=Content&sd=NewPoetry|title=Boloji.com - Poetry|work=boloji.com|access-date=7 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207232410/http://www.boloji.com/index.cfm?md=Content&sd=NewPoetry|archive-date=7 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[George Menachery]] - Historian, author, encyclopaedist, archaeologist, anthropologist, writer of [[Church history|Church History]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.menachery.org | title=Prof. George Menachery}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.indianchristianity.com | title=Welcome to Indian Christianity}}</ref>\n*[[Paul Poovathingal|Fr. Paul Poovathingal]], [[Carnatic music]] singer<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2006/03/31/stories/2006033100330200.htm | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=A rare concert | date=31 March 2006}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christianity in West Bengal]]\n* [[Christianity in India]]\n* [[Christianity in Andhra Pradesh]]\n* [[Christianity in Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Goan Catholics]]\n* [[List of Anglo-Indians]]\n* [[List of Saint Thomas Christians]]\n* [[List of Syro-Malabar Catholics]]\n* [[Mangalorean Catholics]]\n* [[Marathi Christians]]\n* [[Malankara Orthodox Syrian Church]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Indian Christians}}\n[[Category:Indian Christians|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of Indian people|Christians]]\n[[Category:Lists of Christians|Indian]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}This article '''lists notable [[Indian people|Indian]] [[Christians]]'''. The list includes both Indians who lived within India and its predecessor states, and those of Indian ancestry who resided in other countries.\n\n== Freedom fighters ==\n* [[Kali Charan Banerjee]] (1847\u20131902)<ref>{{cite journal |url= http://www.theway.org.uk/Back/s104Gispert-Sauch.pdf |title=Two-Eyed Dialogue: Reflections after Fifty Years |first=George |last=Gispert-Suach |quote=the Rev. Kali Charan Banerjee, himself a convert to the Anglican Church. |journal=The Way |year=2002 |volume=104 (Suppement) |pages=31\u201341 |accessdate=2014-06-10}}</ref>\n*[[Krishna Mohan Banerjee]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Murshid |first=Ghulam |year=2012 |chapter=Banerji, Rev. Krishna Mohan |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Banerji,_Rev._Krishna_Mohan |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>\n*[[Amrit Kaur]]<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Who is an Indian? |first=Judith M. |last=Brown |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NCvZWNkQxkC&pg=PA130 |page=130 |title=Missions, Nationalism and the End of Empire |editor1-first=Stanley |editor1-last=Brian |editor2-first=Alaine M. |editor2-last=Low |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |year=2003 |isbn=978-0-80282-116-4}}</ref>\n*[[Harendra Coomar Mookerjee]]<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Who is an Indian? |first=Judith M. |last=Brown |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2NCvZWNkQxkC&pg=PA129 |page=129 |title=Missions, Nationalism and the End of Empire |editor1-first=Stanley |editor1-last=Brian |editor2-first=Alaine M. |editor2-last=Low |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |year=2003 |isbn=978-0-80282-116-4}}</ref>\n*[[Pandita Ramabai]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Jayawardena |first=Kumari |title=The White Woman's Other Burden : Western Women and South Asia During British Colonial Rule |year=1995 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-13665-707-8 |page=55 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vjdpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA55}}</ref>\n*[[S. K. Rudra]]<ref>{{cite book |last=O'Connor |first=Daniel |title=A Clear Star: C. F. Andrews and India 1904 -1914 |year=2005 |publisher=Chronicle Books |page=37|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m1wJ3zXnSr0C&pg=PA37 |isbn=978-8-18028-023-8}}</ref>\n*[[J.C. Kumarappa]]\n*[[Joseph Baptista]]\n*[[Joachim Alva]]\n\n== Business ==\n\n*[[M. G. George Muthoot]], Chairman of [[Muthoot]] Group<ref>{{cite news |work=Muthoot News |title=The leader, the higher order was looking for |url=http://www.stmarysorthodoxchurchfaridabad.org/images/LayTrustree_MGeorgeMuthoot.pdf |accessdate=2017-02-08 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728061810/http://www.stmarysorthodoxchurchfaridabad.org/images/LayTrustree_MGeorgeMuthoot.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-28}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\n*[[Ajit Jogi]] 1st [[Chief Minister of Chattisgarh]] \n*[[Y. S. Jaganmohan Reddy]] current [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]]\n*[[George Fernandes]] was an Indian trade unionist, statesman, journalist, freethinker \n*[[S C Jamir]] Former Chief Minister of Nagaland, and former Governor of Maharashtra and Odisha. \n*[[Madhusudan Das]]\n*[[A. J. John]], founder leader of Travancore State Congress<ref name=\"auto\">Fr. George Thalian: {{cite web|url=http://geocities.ws/kandathil/kandathil/kandathil.html |title=' ''The Great Archbishop Mar Augustine Kandathil, D. D.: the Outline of a Vocation'' '}}, Mar Louis Memorial Press, 1961</ref> \n* [[Y. S. Rajasekhara Reddy]] (1949\u20132009), former [[Chief Minister of Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.merinews.com/article/ysr-buried-with-full-state-honour-in-idupulapai/15783520.shtml |title=YSR buried with full state honour in Idupulapai |date=5 September 2009 |work=Merinews |first=V. Gopala Krishan |last=Murthy |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref>\n* [[Sangliana]], Police Officer of Karnataka, originally from Mizoram, who also served as a Member of the Parliament of India<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/meghalaya-bjp-puts-its-sole-christian-mp-at/275406/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126102825/http://www.indianexpress.com/news/meghalaya-bjp-puts-its-sole-christian-mp-at/275406/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 January 2013 |title=Meghalaya: BJP puts its sole Christian MP at work |work=Indian Express |date=21 February 2008 |accessdate=2012-05-29}}</ref>\n* [[Lal Thanhawla]], Chief Minister of [[Mizoram]]<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-04-27/guwahati/38861208_1_mnf-mizoram-congress-mizo-national-front | work=The Times Of India | title=Mizo National Front heat on Mizoram CM over 'idol worship' | access-date=27 September 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019051550/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-04-27/guwahati/38861208_1_mnf-mizoram-congress-mizo-national-front | archive-date=19 October 2013 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[A. K. Antony]] Former Kerala Chief minister and Indian defenese minister\n* [[Oommen Chandy]] Former Kerala Chief minister\n* [[Rishang Keishing]] Former Chief Minister of Manipur. \n* [[K. M. Mani]] Previous Minister of Finance and law from Kerala\n* [[Neiphiu Rio]] Chief Minister of Nagaland. \n* [[T. M. Thomas Isaac]] Minister of Finance of Kerala\n* [[P. C. Alexander]] IAS officer, Previous Governor of Tamil Nadu & Maharashtra\n* [[P. C. George]] An MLA from Poonjar, Kerala assembly\n\n== Cinema ==\n*[[Katrina Kaif]], British Indian Bollywood actress, highest paid actress in India,<ref>http://biogtown.com/actress-katrina-kaif-biography-personal-life-marriage-controversy-wiki/</ref> CEO- Kay Beauty \n*[[Samantha Akkineni]],South indian actress\n*[[Nivetha Thomas]],south indian actress\n*[[Vijay (actor)|Vijay]], Kollywood actor<ref>https://tamilglitz.in/the-23-a-tribute-to-ilayathalapathy-vijay-for-his-23-years-of-excellence/</ref>\n*[[Nivin Pauly]], Mollywood actor\n*[[Vikram (actor)]], Kollywood actor\n*[[Tovino Thomas]],Mollywood actor\n*[[Dino Morea]], Hindi cinema actor<ref>{{cite web|title = I've had long conversations with God here: Dino Morea about Mount Mary Church|url = http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-i-ve-had-long-conversations-with-god-here-dino-morea-about-mount-mary-church-1738268|accessdate=2015-10-01}}</ref>\n*[[Johny Lever]], Hindhi cinema actor\n*[[Tiger Prabhakar]], Kannada cinema actor<ref>{{cite web|title = My Dad Prabhakar Did not Die of Gangrene: Vinod Prabhakar - chitraloka.com {{!}} Kannada Movie News, Reviews {{!}} Image|url = http://www.chitraloka.com/interviews/11793-my-dad-prabhakar-did-not-die-of-gangrene-vinod-prabhakar.html|website = www.chitraloka.com|accessdate=2015-10-02|first = Super|last = User}}</ref>\n*\n\n== Sports ==\n* [[Sanju Samson]], cricketer\n* [[Varun Aaron]], cricketer\n*[[Mahesh Bhupathi]], professional tennis player also widely regarded as among the best [[doubles (tennis)|doubles]] players in the world with 11 [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] titles to his credit<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi-times/Shvetha-Mahesh-Why-knot/articleshow/20992167.cms | work=The Times Of India | first=Gauri | last=Sinh | title=Shvetha & Mahesh? Why knot! | date=2 September 2002 |accessdate=2015-04-02}}</ref>\n*[[Vinod Kambli]], cricketer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report_vinod-kambli-embraces-christianity_1435521 |title=Vinod Kambli embraces Christianity - Sport - DNA |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date= 9 September 2010|accessdate=2013-09-25}}</ref>\n*[[Mary Kom]], Olympic bronze medallist in [[2012 Summer Olympics]], London<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.readersdigest.co.in/mary-kom |title=Mary Kom: Full-Confidence Lady |publisher=Reader's Digest |author=Aarti Narang |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227052910/http://www.readersdigest.co.in/mary-kom |archivedate=27 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Religious leaders ==\n\n*[[Philipose Mar Chrysostom|Dr.Philipose Mar Chrysostom]] - Padma Bushan,world record holder for the longest serving bishop in the world, record holder as theme actor in the longest comprehensive biopic documentary ever made<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/malayalam/movies/news/Blessys-biopic-on-Mar-Chrysostom-will-be-72-hours-long/articleshow/52671550.cms|title=Blessy's biopic on Mar Chrysostom will be 72 hours long - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/mohanlal-blessy-back-with-documentary-on-mar-chrysostom.html|title=Mohanlal, Blessy back again for documentary on Mar Chrysostom|website=OnManorama|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>,Metropolitan Emeritus of the [[Mar Thoma Syrian Church]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Mar Thoma|first=Alexander|title=The Syrian heritage and the Mar Thoma Church|date=2011-12-31|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.31826/9781463232931-003|work=The Harp (Volume 2)|pages=9\u201310|publisher=Gorgias Press|isbn=978-1-4632-3293-1|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n*[[Baselios Mar Thoma Paulose II]] - 8th Catholicos of the Malankara & 21st [[Malankara Metropolitan]] (2010\u2013Present).(Supreme head of the [[Malankara  Orthodox Church|Malankara Church]] aka Indian Orthodox Church)\n*[[Andrews Thazhath]] - the third and the [[Metropolitan Archbishop]] of [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Archdiocese of Thrissur]]\n*[[Jacob Thoomkuzhy]] - Catholic Arch Bishop Emeritus and the second [[Metropolitan Archbishop]] of the [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Archdiocese of Thrissur]]\n* [[Joseph Mar Thoma]] - [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan]] of the [[Mar Thoma Syrian Church]].\n* [[Jolly Abraham]] - Leading [[evangelism|evangelist]] [[worship leader]] in South India. Founder of Musi-Care Cultural and Charitable Trust<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/jollee-good-show/article2030431.ece |title=Jollee good show! |work=The Hindu |date=19 May 2011 |accessdate=2016-09-15}}</ref>\n* [[Puroshottam Choudhary]] - preacher, evangelist, writer of [[Christian literature]]\n* [[Aurobindo Nath Mukherjee]] - first Indian [[Anglican Diocese of Calcutta|Bishop of Calcutta]] and [[Metropolitan bishop|Metropolitan of India]]\n* [[Lal Behari Dey]] - Indian journalist, writer, and Christian missionary\n* [[Ravi Zacharias]] - Christian apologist, Founder and Chairman of the Board of Ravi Zacharias International Ministries.\n* [[D. G. S. Dhinakaran]] - Christian evangelist. \n*[[Paul Dhinakaran]], Indian evangelist and the Chancellor of [[Karunya university]], which he owns. \n*[[K. A. Paul]], Evangelist,Philanthropist, Politician and founder of [[Praja Shanti Party]]. \n*[[K. P. Yohannan]], founder and president of [[Gospel for Asia]], He is also the founder and Metropolitan Bishop of [[Believers Eastern Church]]. \n* [[Valerian Gracias]] - First cardinal from India.\n* [[Duraisamy Simon Lourdusamy]] - First Indian to head a [[Sacred Congregation]] of the [[Catholic Church]].\n* [[Acharya K. K. Chandy]] - President Emeritus- Fellowship of Reconciliation India; 1 of the 3 Founding Fathers - Christavashram, Kottayam; Founder Father- Gurukul Ecumenical Centre for Peace. \n* [[Varghese Payyappilly Palakkappilly]] - Founder of the Congregation of the [[Sisters of the Destitute]].\n* [[Mary Celine Payyappilly]] - [[Servant of God]], Professed Religious of the Congregation of the Mother of Carmel.\n* [[George Alencherry]] - [[Catholic Cardinal]] and the Major Archbishop of the [[Syro-Malabar Church]].\n* [[Varkey Vithayathil]] - [[Catholic Cardinal]] and former Major Archbishop of the [[Syro-Malabar Church]].\n* [[Antony Padiyara]] - [[Catholic Cardinal]] and the First Major Archbishop of the [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Church]].\n* [[Joseph Parecattil]] - First from the Syro-Malabar church to be made a [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]].\n* [[Augustine Kandathil]] - First head of the [[Syro-Malabar Church]] and first Indian to assume powers and rule as an [[archbishop]] of the [[Catholic Church]].\n* [[Kuriakose Elias Chavara]] - First Indian to be beatified [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Church]].\n* [[Saint Alphonsa]] - first Indian Catholic to be raised to sainthood [[Syro-Malabar Catholic Church]].\n* [[Mother Teresa]] of Kolkata - Founder of [[Missionaries of Charity]] and the most well-known Christian social worker of India (although Albanian and born in Skopje in Macedonia, she became an Indian).\n* [[V. C. Samuel]] - World-renowned [[Theologian]], [[Historian]], [[Ecumenical]] Leader, [[Professor]]/[[Dean (education)|Dean]] in India and abroad, [[Priest]], [[Indian Orthodox Church]].\n* [[Cyril Baselios]] - Former head of the [[Syro-Malankara Catholic Church]].\n* [[Mariam Thresia]] - [[Syro-Malabar Church]].\n* St. [[Euphrasia]] - [[Syro-Malabar Church]].\n* St. [[Joseph Vaz]] - Goan [[Oratory of Saint Philip Neri|Oratorian]] [[priest]] and missionary to [[Sri Lanka]]\n*[[Rani Maria Vattalil]] - Catholic religious and missionary social worker in the Franciscan Clarist Congregation\n* [[Nidhiry Mani Kathanar]] - Priest of the [[Syro-Malabar Church]] who led a relentless campaign for indigenous bishops. Founder of Nazrani Deepika Malayalam newspaper.\n* [[Neiliezh\u00fc \u00dcsou]] (1941\u20132009), an influential Baptist preacher, theologian, Church musician, music teacher and composer from the [[North-East India|North-Eastern state of India]], [[Nagaland]].\n* [[Baselios Yeldo]] - was the Maphrian of the East of the Syriac Orthodox Church. He was the Catholicos of Jerusalem and Mosul. He is the Saint of Malankara Orthodox, Syriac Orthodox and Jacobite Orthodox Churches.\n* [[Baselios Mar Thoma Mathews I]] - First Catholicos who used Mar Thoma in his title. He was awarded The Order of St. Valdimer by the Patriarch of Russia.\n* [[Antonio Francisco Xavier Alvares]] - First Head of Goan Orthodox who was a Catholic Priest who joined Malankara Orthodox Syrian Church in search for real believes and worship.\n* [[J. W. Gladstone]] - Moderator of the [[Church of South India]].\n* [[K. C. John]] - [[India Pentecostal Church of God]] General President.\n* [[Telesphore Toppo]] - First Indian Cardinal from the Scheduled Tribal communities.\n* [[Devasahayam Pillai]] (1712\u20131752), beatified convert, layman and martyr of the Latin rite of the Roman Catholic Church.\n* [[Geevarghese Mar Gregorios|Geevarghese Gregorios]] - (1848-1902)  First Indian to be raised to sainthood. First Saint of Malankara Church and the youngest one in Malankara to become a Bishop.\n* [[Geevarghese Mar Dionysius of Vattasseril (Dionysius VI)|Geevarghese Dionysius of Vattasseril (Dionysius VI)]] (1858-1934) Malankara Metropolitan and Saint of Malankara Orthodox Church.\n* [[Thomas Fernando]], former Catholic bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tuticorin]]\n* [[Francis Tiburtius Roche]], former Catholic bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tuticorin]]\n* [[Peter Fernando]], former Catholic bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tuticorin]]\n\n=== Others in religious life ===\n*[[Siluvai Ignaci]] - Catholic Priest and Educator from [[Kuthenkuly]]\n* [[Maria Theresa Chiramel]] - Catholic nun.\n* [[Ken Gnanakan]] - Evangelist, singer, environmentalist and Founder Director of Acts Ministries.\n* [[P. C. John]] - [[Kerala Brethren]] person.\n* [[Nirmala Joshi]] - Former Superior General of the [[Missionaries of Charity]].\n* [[Bakht Singh]] - Evangelist, Apostle and Pioneer in local Church planting Ministries in India.\n* [[Sadhu Sundar Singh]] - Missionary, [[Universal Reconciliation|Christian universalist]].\n* [[Sadhu Kochoonju Upadesi]] - Malayali preacher and poet / composer.\n\n== Cultural leaders ==\n*[[Michael Madhusudan Dutt]] - famous Bengali poet and dramatist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boloji.com/index.cfm?md=Content&sd=NewPoetry|title=Boloji.com - Poetry|work=boloji.com|access-date=7 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207232410/http://www.boloji.com/index.cfm?md=Content&sd=NewPoetry|archive-date=7 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[George Menachery]] - Historian, author, encyclopaedist, archaeologist, anthropologist, writer of [[Church history|Church History]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.menachery.org | title=Prof. George Menachery}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.indianchristianity.com | title=Welcome to Indian Christianity}}</ref>\n*[[Paul Poovathingal|Fr. Paul Poovathingal]], [[Carnatic music]] singer<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2006/03/31/stories/2006033100330200.htm | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=A rare concert | date=31 March 2006}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Christianity in West Bengal]]\n* [[Christianity in India]]\n* [[Christianity in Andhra Pradesh]]\n* [[Christianity in Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[Goan Catholics]]\n* [[List of Anglo-Indians]]\n* [[List of Saint Thomas Christians]]\n* [[List of Syro-Malabar Catholics]]\n* [[Mangalorean Catholics]]\n* [[Marathi Christians]]\n* [[Malankara Orthodox Syrian Church]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Indian Christians}}\n[[Category:Indian Christians|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of Indian people|Christians]]\n[[Category:Lists of Christians|Indian]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c5:5304:fc01:d9f2:4376:359a:a8ef", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Indian_Christians"}
{"title_page": "Kerem G\u00f6rsev", "text_new": "[[File:Kerem G\u00f6rsev 2009 OTRS.jpg|thumb|Kerem G\u00f6rsev in 2009]]\n\n'''Kerem G\u00f6rsev''' (b. 28 June 1961<ref name=discogs>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1911189-Kerem-G\u00f6rsev|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev|publisher=discogs.com|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref> in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]) is a Turkish [[jazz]] pianist and composer.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography>{{cite web|url=http://keremgorsev.com/en/biography/|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev: Biography|publisher=keremgorsev.com|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=allaboutjazz>{{cite web|url=https://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/keremgorsev|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev|publisher=allaboutjazz.com|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=turkishjazz>{{cite web|url=https://www.turkishjazz.org/artist/kerem-gorsev|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev|publisher=turkishjazz.org|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKerem G\u00f6rsev was born on 28 June 1961 in Istanbul.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/> He started his musical education at the age of 6 by enrolling in the [[Istanbul Municipal Conservatory]] in 1967.<ref name=allaboutjazz/><ref name=turkishjazz/> In 1972 he began his studies at the [[Istanbul University State Conservatory]], which continued during the next twelve years.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/><ref name=allaboutjazz/><ref name=turkishjazz/>\n\n==Musical career==\nHis passion for [[jazz]] began during his conservatory studies, and until his first record ''Hands and Lips'' was released in 1994, he performed at various jazz clubs with many jazz musicians including Ed Howard, Rabin Kenyata, [[Doris Troy]], Vinnie Night, LaVerne Butler, Allan Harris, [[Clifford Jarvis]], and Harvey Thompson.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/> He has performed in two concerts with the [[Elvin Jones|Elvin Jones Jazz Machine]] at the [[Eski\u015fehir]] Festival in 1999.<ref name=allaboutjazz/><ref name=turkishjazz/>\n\nBetween 1994 and 2018 he released 18 records, including internationally acclaimed works like ''Therapy'' (2010), which was nominated as a candidate for the [[Grammy Award]] under the \u201cGrand Jazz Orchestras\u201d (Best Large Jazz Ensemble) category in 2011.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/kerem-grammye-yuruyor-19016046|title=Kerem Grammy'e y\u00fcr\u00fcyor|publisher=[[H\u00fcrriyet]]|date=2011-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milliyet.com.tr/pembenar/kerem-gorsev-grammy-yolunda-1452088|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev Grammy yolunda|publisher=[[Milliyet]]|date=2011-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://t24.com.tr/haber/kerem-gorsev-grammyye-aday,175708|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev Grammy'ye aday|publisher=t24.com.tr|date=2011-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cazkolik.com/icerik/caz-albumleri-grammy-yolunda-kerem-gorsevin-therapy-okan-ersanin-reborn-journeysi-elemeleri-gecti|title=Caz alb\u00fcmleri Grammy yolunda... Kerem G\u00f6rsev`in Therapy, Okan Ersan`\u0131n Reborn Journey`si elemeleri ge\u00e7ti|publisher=cazkolik.com|date=2011-10-17}}</ref>\n\nKerem G\u00f6rsev completed records at the [[Abbey Road Studios]] in [[London]] and the [[Universal Audio#United Recording Corp.|United Recording Corp.]] in [[Los Angeles]] with world-renowned orchestras including the [[London Philharmonic]], Los Angeles Strings, [[Prague Philharmonic Orchestra|Prague Philharmonic]], and [[St. Petersburg Philharmonic]].<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/> He collaborated with [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-awarded jazz musicians such as [[Alan Broadbent]], [[Ernie Watts]], [[Joe LaBarbera]] and also shared the stage with them in numerous concerts and jazz festivals in Turkey.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/><ref name=akbanksanat>{{cite web|url=https://www.akbanksanat.com/en/event/kerem-gorsev-trio|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev Trio|publisher=akbanksanat.com|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=skylife>{{cite web|url=https://www.skylife.com/en/2018-06-business/have-a-pleasant-flight-with-kerem-gorsev-s-latest-album-after-the-hurricane|title=Have a Pleasant Flight with Kerem G\u00f6rsev\u2019s Latest Album After The Hurricane|publisher=skylife.com|date=June 2018|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref> For his ''Warm Autumn'' (2001) and ''Meeting Point'' (2003) albums, recorded in [[New York City]] between 1998 and 2003, he worked with [[Russell Gunn]], [[Steve Kirby (musician)|Steve Kirby]], [[Alvester Garnett]], [[Marcus Strickland]], [[Eric Revis]] and [[J. D. Allen]], and he also performed with those artists across Turkey.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/><ref name=allaboutjazz/><ref name=turkishjazz/>\n\nAlong with his participation in international jazz festivals such as [[Marciac]], [[Umbria Jazz Festival|Umbria]], [[Pescara Jazz|Pescara]], [[Bologna]], [[Vilnius Jazz Festival|Vilnius]], [[Leopolis Jazz Fest|Lviv]], [[Skopje Jazz Festival|Skopje]] and [[Baku International Jazz Festival|Baku]], he also took the stage in New York City, London, [[Copenhagen]], [[M\u00fcnster]], [[Coesfeld]], [[Hamburg]], [[Cologne]], [[Stuttgart]] and [[Islamabad]].<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/>\n\nKerem G\u00f6rsev is also known for his research and broadcasting work. Since 1997, he has hosted the \u201cKerem G\u00f6rsev\u2019le Jazz\u201d (\u201cJazz with Kerem G\u00f6rsev\u201d) TV show and a series of radio shows, making significant contributions to the promotion and popularization of jazz in Turkey.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/>\n\nDuring trio performances, Ka\u011fan Y\u0131ld\u0131z (contrabass) and [[Ferit Odman]] (drums) accompany Kerem G\u00f6rsev; and the quartet project includes Engin Recepo\u011fullar\u0131\n(saxophone).<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/> Kerem G\u00f6rsev performs at three different projects with a trio, quartet and symphonic orchestra.\n\n==Discography==\n* ''Hands & Lips'' (1994)\n* ''I Love May'' (1995)\n* ''For Murat'' (1996)\n* ''Relaxing'' (1997)\n* ''Laid Back'' (1999)\n* ''November in St. Petersburg'' (2000)\n* ''Warm Autumn'' (2001)\n* ''Existence'' (2002)\n* ''Meeting Point'' (2003)\n* ''Orange Juice'' (2005)\n* ''Back Again'' (2007)\n* ''Diversion'' (2008)\n* ''Therapy'' (2010)\n* ''To Bill Evans'' (2013)\n* ''Emirgan'' (2014)\n* ''Four Days'' (2015)\n* ''Spring Water'' (2017)\n* ''After The Hurricane'' (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://keremgorsev.com/ Official website of Kerem G\u00f6rsev]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Turkish jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Turkish jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:Turkish pianists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kerem G\u00f6rsev 2009 OTRS.jpg|thumb|Kerem G\u00f6rsev in 2009]]\n\n'''Kerem G\u00f6rsev''' (b. 28 June 1961<ref name=discogs>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1911189-Kerem-G\u00f6rsev|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev|publisher=discogs.com|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref> in [[Istanbul]], [[Turkey]]) is a Turkish [[jazz]] pianist and composer.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography>{{cite web|url=http://keremgorsev.com/en/biography/|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev: Biography|publisher=keremgorsev.com|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=allaboutjazz>{{cite web|url=https://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/keremgorsev|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev|publisher=allaboutjazz.com|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=turkishjazz>{{cite web|url=https://www.turkishjazz.org/artist/kerem-gorsev|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev|publisher=turkishjazz.org|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKerem G\u00f6rsev was born on 28 June 1961 in Istanbul.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/> He started his musical education at the age of 6 by enrolling in the [[Istanbul Municipal Conservatory]] in 1967.<ref name=allaboutjazz/><ref name=turkishjazz/> In 1972 he began his studies at the [[Istanbul University State Conservatory]], which continued during the next twelve years.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/><ref name=allaboutjazz/><ref name=turkishjazz/>\n\n==Musical career==\nHis passion for [[jazz]] began during his conservatory studies, and until his first record ''Hands and Lips'' was released in 1994, he performed at various jazz clubs with many jazz musicians including Ed Howard, Rabin Kenyata, [[Doris Troy]], Vinnie Night, LaVerne Butler, Allan Harris, [[Clifford Jarvis]], and Harvey Thompson.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/> He has performed in two concerts with the [[Elvin Jones|Elvin Jones Jazz Machine]] at the [[Eski\u015fehir]] Festival in 1999.<ref name=allaboutjazz/><ref name=turkishjazz/>\n\nBetween 1994 and 2018 he released 18 records, including internationally acclaimed works like ''Therapy'' (2010), which was nominated as a candidate for the [[Grammy Award]] under the \u201cGrand Jazz Orchestras\u201d (Best Large Jazz Ensemble) category in 2011.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/gundem/kerem-grammye-yuruyor-19016046|title=Kerem Grammy'e y\u00fcr\u00fcyor|publisher=[[H\u00fcrriyet]]|date=2011-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milliyet.com.tr/pembenar/kerem-gorsev-grammy-yolunda-1452088|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev Grammy yolunda|publisher=[[Milliyet]]|date=2011-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://t24.com.tr/haber/kerem-gorsev-grammyye-aday,175708|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev Grammy'ye aday|publisher=t24.com.tr|date=2011-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cazkolik.com/icerik/caz-albumleri-grammy-yolunda-kerem-gorsevin-therapy-okan-ersanin-reborn-journeysi-elemeleri-gecti|title=Caz alb\u00fcmleri Grammy yolunda... Kerem G\u00f6rsev`in Therapy, Okan Ersan`\u0131n Reborn Journey`si elemeleri ge\u00e7ti|publisher=cazkolik.com|date=2011-10-17}}</ref>\n\nKerem G\u00f6rsev completed records at the [[Abbey Road Studios]] in [[London]] and the [[Universal Audio#United Recording Corp.|United Recording Corp.]] in [[Los Angeles]] with world-renowned orchestras including the [[London Philharmonic]], Los Angeles Strings, [[Prague Philharmonic Orchestra|Prague Philharmonic]], and [[St. Petersburg Philharmonic]].<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/> He collaborated with [[Grammy Award|Grammy]]-awarded jazz musicians such as [[Alan Broadbent]], [[Ernie Watts]], [[Joe LaBarbera]] and also shared the stage with them in numerous concerts and jazz festivals in Turkey.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/><ref name=akbanksanat>{{cite web|url=https://www.akbanksanat.com/en/event/kerem-gorsev-trio|title=Kerem G\u00f6rsev Trio|publisher=akbanksanat.com|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=skylife>{{cite web|url=https://www.skylife.com/en/2018-06-business/have-a-pleasant-flight-with-kerem-gorsev-s-latest-album-after-the-hurricane|title=Have a Pleasant Flight with Kerem G\u00f6rsev\u2019s Latest Album After The Hurricane|publisher=skylife.com|date=June 2018|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref> For his ''Warm Autumn'' (2001) and ''Meeting Point'' (2003) albums, recorded in [[New York City]] between 1998 and 2003, he worked with [[Russell Gunn]], [[Steve Kirby]], [[Alvester Garnett]], [[Marcus Strickland]], [[Eric Revis]] and [[J. D. Allen]], and he also performed with those artists across Turkey.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/><ref name=allaboutjazz/><ref name=turkishjazz/>\n\nAlong with his participation in international jazz festivals such as [[Marciac]], [[Umbria Jazz Festival|Umbria]], [[Pescara Jazz|Pescara]], [[Bologna]], [[Vilnius Jazz Festival|Vilnius]], [[Leopolis Jazz Fest|Lviv]], [[Skopje Jazz Festival|Skopje]] and [[Baku International Jazz Festival|Baku]], he also took the stage in New York City, London, [[Copenhagen]], [[M\u00fcnster]], [[Coesfeld]], [[Hamburg]], [[Cologne]], [[Stuttgart]] and [[Islamabad]].<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/>\n\nKerem G\u00f6rsev is also known for his research and broadcasting work. Since 1997, he has hosted the \u201cKerem G\u00f6rsev\u2019le Jazz\u201d (\u201cJazz with Kerem G\u00f6rsev\u201d) TV show and a series of radio shows, making significant contributions to the promotion and popularization of jazz in Turkey.<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/>\n\nDuring trio performances, Ka\u011fan Y\u0131ld\u0131z (contrabass) and [[Ferit Odman]] (drums) accompany Kerem G\u00f6rsev; and the quartet project includes Engin Recepo\u011fullar\u0131\n(saxophone).<ref name=kerem-gorsev-biography/> Kerem G\u00f6rsev performs at three different projects with a trio, quartet and symphonic orchestra.\n\n==Discography==\n* ''Hands & Lips'' (1994)\n* ''I Love May'' (1995)\n* ''For Murat'' (1996)\n* ''Relaxing'' (1997)\n* ''Laid Back'' (1999)\n* ''November in St. Petersburg'' (2000)\n* ''Warm Autumn'' (2001)\n* ''Existence'' (2002)\n* ''Meeting Point'' (2003)\n* ''Orange Juice'' (2005)\n* ''Back Again'' (2007)\n* ''Diversion'' (2008)\n* ''Therapy'' (2010)\n* ''To Bill Evans'' (2013)\n* ''Emirgan'' (2014)\n* ''Four Days'' (2015)\n* ''Spring Water'' (2017)\n* ''After The Hurricane'' (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://keremgorsev.com/ Official website of Kerem G\u00f6rsev]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Turkish jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Turkish jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:Turkish pianists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSteve Kirby(link changed toSteve Kirby (musician)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerem_G%C3%B6rsev"}
{"title_page": "Happy Wheels", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Happy Wheels\n| image = Happy Wheels Logo.png\n| developer = Fancy Force\n| publisher = Fancy Force\n| platforms = [[Web browser]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| released = {{Unbulleted list|'''Browser'''|June 4, 2010|'''iOS'''|August 20, 2015|'''Android'''|January 25, 2020}}\n| genre = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| designer = Jim Bonacci\n| programmer = Jim Bonacci\n| artist = Jim Bonacci\n| composer = Jack Zankowski\n}}\n\n'''''Happy Wheels''''' is a [[ragdoll physics]]-based [[Platform game|platform]] [[browser game]] developed and published by American studio Fancy Force. Created by [[video game designer]] Jim Bonacci in 2010, the game features several [[player character]]s, who use different, sometimes atypical, vehicles to traverse the game's many levels. The game is best known for its [[graphic violence]] and the amount of [[user-generated content]] its players produce on a regular basis, with game maps shared on a public server.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Happy Wheels''{{'}} [[tagline]] is \"Choose your inadequately prepared racer, and ignore severe consequences in your desperate search for victory!\"<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamesetwatch.com/2010/10/happy_wheels_bloody_severe_con.php | title = Happy Wheels: Bloody, 'Severe Consequences' | last = Caoili | first = Eric| date = October 25, 2010 | website = [[GameSetWatch]] | publisher = [[UBM TechWeb]] | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> The actual mechanics of gameplay vary because of character choice and level design;<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/06/02/best-free-games?page=10 | title = Best Free Games - Page 10 of 17 | date = June 2, 2011 | last = Meunier | first = Nathan | website = [[IGN]] | publisher = [[IGN Entertainment]] | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> the game includes characters such as a businessman on a [[Segway]].<ref name=\"Thier\">{{cite news|last1=Thier|first1=Dave|title=Gruesome 'Happy Wheels' Shoots To The Top Of The App Store|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidthier/2015/08/28/gruesome-happy-wheels-shoots-to-the-top-of-the-app-store/#75f3152b23e4|accessdate=6 August 2017|work=Forbes}}</ref>\n\nThe goal of the game also differs depending on the level. In most levels, the goal is to reach a finish line or to collect tokens. Many levels feature alternate or nonexistent goals for the player.<ref name=\"IGN\" /><ref name=\"The Creators Project\">{{cite web | url = http://thecreatorsproject.vice.com/blog/severed-limbs-and-slam-dunked-toddlers-an-interview-with-the-creator-of-happy-wheels | title = Severed Limbs and Slam-Dunked Toddlers: An Interview With The Creator of \"Happy Wheels\" | last = Holmes | first = Kevin | date = October 28, 2010 | website = [[The Creators Project]] | publisher = [[Vice Media]] | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nReviewers have noted that ''Happy Wheels'' exhibits graphic violence in its gameplay.<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\" /><ref name=\"IGN\" /><ref name=\"The Creators Project\" /><ref name=\"TheSixthAxis\">{{cite web | url = http://www.thesixthaxis.com/2012/02/01/cheap-pc-gaming-three-more-cheap-distractions/ | title = Cheap PC Gaming: Three More Cheap Distractions | last = Chadwick | first = Gareth | date = February 1, 2012 | website = TheSixthAxis | publisher = Oscar Mike Media | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> For instance, characters can be [[Decapitation|decapitated]], shot, or crushed by different obstacles.<ref name=\"TheSixthAxis\" /> Loss of limbs and animated blood loss are also graphic elements.<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\" /><ref name=\"IGN\" />\n\nPlayers also have the choice to upload [[Instant replay|replays]] of their level attempts, which can then be viewed.<ref name=\"IGN\" />\n\n''Happy Wheels'' features a level editor, which allows players to create custom levels of their own. It contains a plethora of tools and objects for level building. Users can upload their maps to a public server where they are accessible.<ref name=\"TheSixthAxis\" />\n\n== Development ==\nIndie game developer Jim Bonacci, largely the programmer and artist for the game,<ref name=\"The Creators Project\" /> began work on the game in 2006.<ref name=\"TjfToday\">{{cite web | url = http://tjftoday.webs.com/apps/blog/show/13399601-interview-jim-bonacci | title = Interview: JIM BONACCI | author = 456jerkface | date = March 21, 2012 | website = TjfToday | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> Bonacci has said that his inspiration for the game came from other ragdoll physics-based games in the [[browser game]]s community,<ref name=\"The Creators Project\" /> as his friend and former boss, Alec Cove, had made a verlet physics engine for flash.<ref name=\"TjfToday\" /> Bonacci said that \"[he] was messing around with it, and eventually created a guy in a wheelchair that would endlessly fall down a random hill. [He] thought it was funny and stupid, so [he] kept expanding on it. It was only meant to be a very small game, but eventually it became [his] main focus.\"<ref name=\"TjfToday\" />\n\nIn addition, he explained the violent nature of the game in terms of his frustration with how consequences of certain actions were not treated realistically in other game titles, as he stated that \"it always bothered [him] when... you'd fall off your vehicle and harmlessly bounce around. In other cases, you would have the same canned animation over and over. [He's] not sure if it was a lack of detail or concern on the part of the developer, but the consequences of your in-game actions were often improperly illustrated. For [him], half of the fun of playing a game that imitates life (sort of), is making mistakes and seeing the end result.\"<ref name=\"The Creators Project\" />\n\nBonacci also noted that, because gameplay would often involve the player dying repeatedly, he put a great deal of effort into making that part of the game enjoyable.<ref name=\"The Creators Project\" />\n\nThe full version of ''Happy Wheels'' is only available on Bonacci's original website,<ref name=\"TjfToday\" /> and demo versions of the game are licensed to other websites. These demo versions only include a limited number of featured maps and selectable characters.\n\nThere are approximately 5 million user-generated levels. The total count of level plays is over 13 billion.\n\nCurrently, Jason Schymick helps Bonacci work on the game programming, although different people have contributed. \"The others who helped are all amazing\", says Bonnaci.<ref name=\"TjfToday\" />{{Failed verification|date=December 2017|reason=That quote is not in that link.}} Alec Cove joined Fancy Force in 2013 and handles all serverside architecture and development.<ref name=\"New Site\">{{cite web | url = http://www.totaljerkface.com/news_comments.tjf?nid=68 | title = NEW SITE, YAY | last = Bonacci | first = Jim | date = March 13, 2015 | website = Totaljerkface.com | publisher = Fancy Force | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2014, Schymick announced that a [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] ports of the game have been in development.<ref name=\"In Progress\">{{cite web | url = http://www.totaljerkface.com/news_comments.tjf?nid=73 | title = Happy Wheels iOS In Progress\u2026 | last = Schymick | first = Jason | date = September 30, 2014 | website = Totaljerkface.com | publisher = Fancy Force | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> The iOS version was released as a free download through the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] on August 20, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/067107/popular-flash-game-happy-wheels-makes-its-ios-debut/ |title=Popular flash game Happy Wheels makes its iOS debut |first=Christian |last=Valentin |date=August 20, 2015 |website=[[Pocket Gamer]]}}</ref> For the Android version, Fancy Force began accepting beta test applications in October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/081302/happy-wheels-developer-fancy-force-is-bringing-their-popular-game-to-android-and-you-can-sign-up-to-be-part-of-the-beta-now/ |title=Happy Wheels developer Fancy Force is bringing their popular game to Android and you can sign up to be part of the beta now |first=Stephen |last=Gregson-Wood |date=October 14, 2019 |website=[[Pocket Gamer]]}}</ref> Following a beta testing phase, the finished version was released on January 25, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/082020/happy-wheels-is-available-now-for-android-following-a-brief-stint-in-beta/ |title=Happy Wheels is available now for Android following a brief stint in beta last year |first=Stephen |last=Gregson-Wood |date=January 27, 2020 |website=[[Pocket Gamer]]}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = iOS: 73/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/happy-wheels |title=Happy Wheels for iPhone/iPad Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Happy Wheels'' has received generally positive reviews. It was recommended by [[GameSetWatch]]<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\" /> and considered one of the \"Best Free Games\" by [[IGN]].<ref name=\"IGN\" /> Its level editor and amount of user-generated content have received praise from reviewers.<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\" /><ref name=\"Hindustan Times\">{{cite web | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/tech-reviews/littlebigplanet-vita-dated-for-september/story-aGc3elIbMPIbCG6moiJgPJ.html | title = 'LittleBigPlanet' Vita dated for September | last = Alam | first = Shafiq | date = August 4, 2012 | website = [[Hindustan Times]] | publisher = [[HT Media]] | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> The over-the-top nature of the violence is a central theme of the game,<ref name=\"Thier\" /> and some reviewers have considered it humorous;<ref name=\"IGN\" /> one review stated that \"It is so genuinely difficult to play ''Happy Wheels'' and not just laugh and laugh at the ridiculous ways in which your character can be torn into pieces.\"<ref name=\"TheSixthAxis\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Vehicle simulation game]]\n* [[Grand Theft Auto (series)|Grand Theft Auto]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://totaljerkface.com/happy_wheels.tjf}} {{plays audio}}\n\n[[Category:2010 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Browser games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Platform games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Blood in fiction]]\n[[Category:Video game controversies]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in video games]]\n[[Category:Satirical video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Happy Wheels\n| image = Happy Wheels Logo.png\n| developer = Fancy Force\n| publisher = Fancy Force\n| platforms = [[Web browser]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| released = {{Unbulleted list|'''Browser'''|June 4, 2010|'''iOS'''|August 20, 2015|'''Android'''|January 25, 2020}}\n| genre = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| designer = Jim Bonacci\n| programmer = Jim Bonacci\n| artist = Jim Bonacci\n| composer = Jack Zankowski\n}}\n\n'''''Happy Wheels''''' is a [[ragdoll physics]]-based [[Platform game|platform]] [[browser game]] developed and published by American studio Fancy Force. Created by [[video game designer]] Jim Bonacci in 2010, the game features several [[player character]]s, who use different, sometimes atypical, vehicles to traverse the game's many levels. The game is best known for its [[graphic violence]] and the amount of [[user-generated content]] its players produce on a regular basis, with game maps shared on a public server.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Happy Wheels''{{'}} [[tagline]] is \"Choose your inadequately prepared racer, and ignore severe consequences in your desperate search for victory!\"<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\">{{cite web | url = http://www.gamesetwatch.com/2010/10/happy_wheels_bloody_severe_con.php | title = Happy Wheels: Bloody, 'Severe Consequences' | last = Caoili | first = Eric| date = October 25, 2010 | website = [[GameSetWatch]] | publisher = [[UBM TechWeb]] | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> The actual mechanics of gameplay vary because of character choice and level design;<ref name=\"IGN\">{{cite web | url = http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/06/02/best-free-games?page=10 | title = Best Free Games - Page 10 of 17 | date = June 2, 2011 | last = Meunier | first = Nathan | website = [[IGN]] | publisher = [[IGN Entertainment]] | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> the game includes characters such as a businessman on a [[Segway]].<ref name=\"Thier\">{{cite news|last1=Thier|first1=Dave|title=Gruesome 'Happy Wheels' Shoots To The Top Of The App Store|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidthier/2015/08/28/gruesome-happy-wheels-shoots-to-the-top-of-the-app-store/#75f3152b23e4|accessdate=6 August 2017|work=Forbes}}</ref>\n\nThe goal of the game also differs depending on the level. In most levels, the goal is to reach a finish line or to collect tokens. Many levels feature alternate or nonexistent goals for the player.<ref name=\"IGN\" /><ref name=\"The Creators Project\">{{cite web | url = http://thecreatorsproject.vice.com/blog/severed-limbs-and-slam-dunked-toddlers-an-interview-with-the-creator-of-happy-wheels | title = Severed Limbs and Slam-Dunked Toddlers: An Interview With The Creator of \"Happy Wheels\" | last = Holmes | first = Kevin | date = October 28, 2010 | website = [[The Creators Project]] | publisher = [[Vice Media]] | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nReviewers have noted that ''Happy Wheels'' exhibits graphic violence in its gameplay.<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\" /><ref name=\"IGN\" /><ref name=\"The Creators Project\" /><ref name=\"TheSixthAxis\">{{cite web | url = http://www.thesixthaxis.com/2012/02/01/cheap-pc-gaming-three-more-cheap-distractions/ | title = Cheap PC Gaming: Three More Cheap Distractions | last = Chadwick | first = Gareth | date = February 1, 2012 | website = TheSixthAxis | publisher = Oscar Mike Media | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> For instance, characters can be [[Decapitation|decapitated]], shot, or crushed by different obstacles.<ref name=\"TheSixthAxis\" /> Loss of limbs and animated blood loss are also graphic elements.<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\" /><ref name=\"IGN\" />\n\nPlayers also have the choice to upload [[Instant replay|replays]] of their level attempts, which can then be viewed.<ref name=\"IGN\" />\n\n''Happy Wheels'' features a level editor, which allows players to create custom levels of their own. It contains a plethora of tools and objects for level building. Users can upload their maps to a public server where they are accessible.<ref name=\"TheSixthAxis\" />\n\n== Development ==\nIndie game developer Jim Bonacci, largely the programmer and artist for the game,<ref name=\"The Creators Project\" /> began work on the game in 2006.<ref name=\"TjfToday\">{{cite web | url = http://tjftoday.webs.com/apps/blog/show/13399601-interview-jim-bonacci | title = Interview: JIM BONACCI | author = 456jerkface | date = March 21, 2012 | website = TjfToday | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> Bonacci has said that his inspiration for the game came from other ragdoll physics-based games in the [[browser game]]s community,<ref name=\"The Creators Project\" /> as his friend and former boss, Alec Cove, had made a verlet physics engine for flash.<ref name=\"TjfToday\" /> Bonacci said that \"[he] was messing around with it, and eventually created a guy in a wheelchair that would endlessly fall down a random hill. [He] thought it was funny and stupid, so [he] kept expanding on it. It was only meant to be a very small game, but eventually it became [his] main focus.\"<ref name=\"TjfToday\" />\n\nIn addition, he explained the violent nature of the game in terms of his frustration with how consequences of certain actions were not treated realistically in other game titles, as he stated that \"it always bothered [him] when... you'd fall off your vehicle and harmlessly bounce around. In other cases, you would have the same canned animation over and over. [He's] not sure if it was a lack of detail or concern on the part of the developer, but the consequences of your in-game actions were often improperly illustrated. For [him], half of the fun of playing a game that imitates life (sort of), is making mistakes and seeing the end result.\"<ref name=\"The Creators Project\" />\n\nBonacci also noted that, because gameplay would often involve the player dying repeatedly, he put a great deal of effort into making that part of the game enjoyable.<ref name=\"The Creators Project\" />\n\nThe full version of ''Happy Wheels'' is only available on Bonacci's original website,<ref name=\"TjfToday\" /> and demo versions of the game are licensed to other websites. These demo versions only include a limited number of featured maps and selectable characters.\n\nThere are approximately 5 million user-generated levels. The total count of level plays is over 13 billion.\n\nCurrently, Jason Schymick helps Bonacci work on the game programming, although different people have contributed. \"The others who helped are all amazing\", says Bonnaci.<ref name=\"TjfToday\" />{{Failed verification|date=December 2017|reason=That quote is not in that link.}} Alec Cove joined Fancy Force in 2013 and handles all serverside architecture and development.<ref name=\"New Site\">{{cite web | url = http://www.totaljerkface.com/news_comments.tjf?nid=68 | title = NEW SITE, YAY | last = Bonacci | first = Jim | date = March 13, 2015 | website = Totaljerkface.com | publisher = Fancy Force | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2014, Schymick announced that a [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] ports of the game have been in development.<ref name=\"In Progress\">{{cite web | url = http://www.totaljerkface.com/news_comments.tjf?nid=73 | title = Happy Wheels iOS In Progress\u2026 | last = Schymick | first = Jason | date = September 30, 2014 | website = Totaljerkface.com | publisher = Fancy Force | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> The iOS version was released as a free download through the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] on August 20, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/067107/popular-flash-game-happy-wheels-makes-its-ios-debut/ |title=Popular flash game Happy Wheels makes its iOS debut |first=Christian |last=Valentin |date=August 20, 2015 |website=[[Pocket Gamer]]}}</ref> For the Android version, Fancy Force began accepting beta test applications in October 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/081302/happy-wheels-developer-fancy-force-is-bringing-their-popular-game-to-android-and-you-can-sign-up-to-be-part-of-the-beta-now/ |title=Happy Wheels developer Fancy Force is bringing their popular game to Android and you can sign up to be part of the beta now |first=Stephen |last=Gregson-Wood |date=October 14, 2019 |website=[[Pocket Gamer]]}}</ref> Following a beta testing phase, the finished version was released on January 25, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/082020/happy-wheels-is-available-now-for-android-following-a-brief-stint-in-beta/ |title=Happy Wheels is available now for Android following a brief stint in beta last year |first=Stephen |last=Gregson-Wood |date=January 27, 2020 |website=[[Pocket Gamer]]}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = iOS: 73/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/happy-wheels |title=Happy Wheels for iPhone/iPad Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 19, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Happy Wheels'' has received generally positive reviews. It was recommended by [[GameSetWatch]]<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\" /> and considered one of the \"Best Free Games\" by [[IGN]].<ref name=\"IGN\" /> Its level editor and amount of user-generated content have received praise from reviewers.<ref name=\"GameSetWatch\" /><ref name=\"Hindustan Times\">{{cite web | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/tech-reviews/littlebigplanet-vita-dated-for-september/story-aGc3elIbMPIbCG6moiJgPJ.html | title = 'LittleBigPlanet' Vita dated for September | last = Alam | first = Shafiq | date = August 4, 2012 | website = [[Hindustan Times]] | publisher = [[HT Media]] | accessdate = October 31, 2015}}</ref> The over-the-top nature of the violence is a central theme of the game,<ref name=\"Thier\" /> and some reviewers have considered it humorous;<ref name=\"IGN\" /> one review stated that \"It is so genuinely difficult to play ''Happy Wheels'' and not just laugh and laugh at the ridiculous ways in which your character can be torn into pieces.\"<ref name=\"TheSixthAxis\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://totaljerkface.com/happy_wheels.tjf}} {{plays audio}}\n\n[[Category:2010 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Browser games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Platform games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Blood in fiction]]\n", "name_user": "112.209.215.22", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Happy_Wheels"}
